{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e02ad69-d13e-410a-b8da-cf6e8e516039","content":"## What happened\n\n.NET 10 adds **implicit conversions from `T[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`**. This changes overload resolution: `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)`.\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, which expression trees cannot represent. The expression tree compiler/interpreter chokes on the Span-based overload.\n\n## How to fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload. Either:\n\n**Option A — Cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth force resolution back to the `IEnumerable<T>` extension method, avoiding the ref struct entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"751e6129-28c4-4f96-aab7-1921659627eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays, specifically when using `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)`.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), which changes how extension methods are resolved.\n\nBut more specifically, the issue here is likely related to how `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<T>()` is resolved on arrays.\n\n\nActually, I think the real culprit is that .NET 10 added implicit conversions from `T[]` to `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`. This means when calling `.Contains()` on an array, the compiler now prefers `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`, and this preference carries through to expression tree compilation.\n\nThe problem is that `Span<T>` is a ref struct, which expression trees can't handle. So in .NET 9, `array.Contains(num)` resolved to the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains` method and worked fine in expression trees. But in .NET 10, the same call now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` with its ref struct parameter, which either fails to compile or throws a runtime error when used in an expression tree context. The most likely culprit is a breaking change in .NET 10 where arrays now implicitly convert to `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, causing `MemoryExtensions.Contains` to be preferred over `Enumerable.Contains`. Since expression trees can't represent calls involving `Span<T>` (a ref struct), this would fail—but the question is whether it fails at compile time when building the expression or at runtime when interpreting it. The implicit conversion from `int[]` to `ReadOnlySpan<int>` is now more specific than the conversion to `IEnumerable<int>`, so overload resolution picks `MemoryExtensions.Contains` instead of `Enumerable.Contains`. But since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a ref struct, the compiler should reject this in an expression tree context with a compile error, not a runtime error—unless the user is experiencing something else entirely. Maybe the real issue is with how the expression tree interpreter handles this in .NET 10, or there's a breaking change in overload resolution when implicit span conversions come into play. The safest fix would be to explicitly call `Enumerable.Contains()` instead of relying on the implicit method resolution.\n\nWriting the corrected expression... structs like `ReadOnlySpan<T>` can't be used in expression trees, so the compiler would reject this at compile time rather than failing at runtime. The fix is to explicitly cast to `IEnumerable<int>` or call `Enumerable.Contains` directly to force the old overload resolution. I'll go with explaining the Span overload resolution as the root cause, since that's the most documented breaking change for this scenario.","outputTokens":2676,"requestId":"7033:E3CA7:5993202:6116D65:69FBE25D"},"id":"fb118f5e-5401-4c6d-8abe-9f5e71e48373","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:53:49.742Z","parentId":"e9f0f9b8-e1b9-406c-a20d-76ad8c4d5f85"}
